1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Bb4 {. Welcome to the other Ruy Lopez,
the Symmetrical Four Knights Spanish. We force Black into a Lopez-like
position, but deprive him of his Lopez theoretical knowledge and also a tempo.
--- When I was young, penniless, thin and handsome, I recall many a dismal
chess tournament breakfast. All I could afford was a cup of tea and a bland
bowl of oatmeal. I could do no more than peer with longing at the six-course
breakfast consumed by the guy at the next table. With the Symmetrical Four
Knights Spanish the same fate befalls Black. We deprive our booked-up Ruy
Lopez expert his pancakes, eggs, hash browns and fruit, and instead hand him a
lukewarm bowl of mush and order him to eat it - and like it! In the opening,
our options are a form of wealth. When Black enters this line we bankrupt his
options, forcing him to enter and play what is given him. --- People
accustomed to power - and I place the super booked up Black side of the Lopez
players firmly in this category - don't take kindly to refusal. Most players
as Black don't want to endure symmetry a move down, so they normally go for
the Unpin line, shown after} 5. O-O O-O 6. d3 Bxc3 7. bxc3 d6 8. Bg5 Qe7 9. Re1
Nd8 10. d4 Ne6 {. The happy news for us is the discovery} 11. Bd2 $1 {
, which makes Black's life rather miserable in what is essentially his only
logical way to play for the win. Carefully study Cheparinov-Jakovenko and
Radjabov-Amin to get a glimpse of Black's anguish in this main line.} *

