1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. Bb5 Nd4 {. We enter our most theoretically
challenging chapter in the entire book. The hair trigger lines of the
Rubinstein Gambit - our version of the Ruy Lopez Marshall Gambit - run sharp
as deceit. In each case, Black offers his e5-pawn, often with future
generosity to follow. The time taken to grab the pawn gives our opponents a
development lead and Marshall Gambit-like attack/initiative as compensation.
In a chess game, one's wealth isn't always measured in scarcity or abundance
of material. In this instance, we are rich in pawns while Black's wealth is
his piece activity. It is our job to master this line to the point where we
snatch our opponents' pawns and then slowly learn to unravel and take the air
out of their initiative and attack. When we reach this glorious moment, it
will feel similar to when Rocky Balboa cried out "Adrian!" --- This isn't a
chapter where we can wing it and play intuitively. We must memorize and
thoroughly understand our defensive plans. One great advantage of the Four
Knights Rubinstein Spanish over the Ruy Lopez Marshall Gambit is that Black
doesn't face the Four Knights Spanish nearly as often as he does the Ruy Lopez.
So it is quite likely that we will be more booked up than our opponents.} *

