1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Nc3 Nf6 4. d4 exd4 5. Nd5 {. Welcome to a hallucinatory
no-man's land where normal rules cease to apply - also known as the Belgrade
Gambit. When I first began this book I had no intention of putting in a
chapter on the Belgrade Gambit, which I then regarded as an opening of dubious
parentage and an assault to logic. At about this time at a tournament, a 2300+
friend told me he tended to lose when he faced the Belgrade, mainly due to his
frantic attempts to bust the gambit. What? This is a line which most titled
players claim is refuted! That was enough for me to reverse course and insert
this chapter in the book. The opening may even turn out to be sound, mainly
thanks to the pioneering work of my friend, Bruce Monson, an IM-strength
correspondence player and advocate for his beloved gambit. What I discovered
when researching the line is that not every gamble ends in ruin, nor does each
adventure end in death. The gambit appeals less to our intellect than it does
to our fighting spirit and gambler's instinct within. So if you are the kind
of person who gets tempted to fly a kite in a hurricane, then you may want to
consider the Belgrade Gambit as a must-win, surprise weapon in your opening
arsenal.} *

